Now let me check what `ValType` constructor takes for the normalized type. Looking at `ValueFromType`, it takes a `ValType` and creates `RefVariant(Type)`. The `RefVariant(ValType)` constructor just stores the type and a null pointer.

So the fix is to change the code to normalize the type:

```cpp
// Push local variables into the stack.
for (auto &Def : Func.getLocals()) {
    for (uint32_t I = 0; I < Def.first; I++) {
        auto InitVal = ValueFromType(Def.second);
        if (Def.second.isRefType() && !Def.second.isAbsHeapType()) {
            auto BotType = toBottomType(StackMgr, Def.second);
            InitVal = RefVariant(ValType(TypeCode::RefNull, BotType));
        }
        StackMgr.push(InitVal);
    }
}
```

This is clean but a bit verbose. Let me simplify by using the same approach as the table fix. Actually, we can just always normalize the ref type by creating a new ValType:

```cpp
for (auto &Def : Func.getLocals()) {
    for (uint32_t I = 0; I < Def.first; I++) {
        if (Def.second.isRefType() && !Def.second.isAbsHeapType()) {
            auto BotType = toBottomType(StackMgr, Def.second);
            StackMgr.push(
                RefVariant(ValType(TypeCode::RefNull, BotType)));
        } else {
            StackMgr.push(ValueFromType(Def.second));
        }
    }
}
```

